&nbsp;

<span style="color: #333333; font-size: 26px;">STEEMIT: WHAT IT IS</span>

&nbsp;

<a href="https://steemit.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Steemit</a>, which was launched on July 4th, 2016, is a social media platform that runs on <a href="http://bitcoinbuildify.com/index.php/2018/03/28/what-is-blockchain-technology/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">blockchain technology</a>(I told you blockchain has <a href="http://bitcoinbuildify.com/index.php/2018/04/14/10-industries-that-could-use-block-chain-technology/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">a lot of different uses</a>). It also has its own cryptocurrency, the STEEM token, which is used to reward content creators and curators according to their level of effort and the general reception of their work by audiences on the platform. As of May 17, 2018, Steemit had accumulated over <a href="https://www.ccn.com/major-milestone-steem-blockchain-hits-1-million-accounts/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1 million active accounts</a> and is currently showing no signs of slowing down. Although still somewhat obscure, Steemit is slowly but surely seeing a growing base of loyal "Steemians", as they are called, and is proving to be an extremely innovative platform drawing an increasing amount of interest and talent from across the internet.

&nbsp;

In this post, I will attempt to give a general overview of this fascinating platform in as clear and honest a way as I can. A basic understanding of crypto currencies and blockchain technology (no, they're not the same ;-) ) would be helpful but is not totally necessary. Also, it's likely that if you do get involved with Steemit, your interest and curiousity in how it works will likely bring you the understanding you need anyway. There is also no shortage of fellow "Steemians" to help you with your questions.

&nbsp;
<h2>THE BASICS</h2>
&nbsp;

The vast majority of Steemit content consists of blog type articles complete with the typical imagery and video supplements one would expect from such a site. There is also a large amount of activity in the comments and discussion around content good enough to warrant it. This is likely why even the founders of the platform refer to Steemit as a "social media site" and not strictly a blogging platform. The rather unique, blockchain based interface combined with the sheer amount of content on the site can be somewhat overwhelming so it's a very good idea to read through the "To Do List" via the "Welcome" link and the FAQ both available by clicking on the top right menu button.

For more general, non-content related matters, <a href="https://steemit.chat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Steemit Chat</a>(a separate website)is recommended as a way to network, make connections, solve issues and promote content. It's perfectly fine to simply stick with a Steemit account and figure it out for yourself but signing up for a Steemit Chat account will likely prove very helpful for a number of reasons considering you can:

&nbsp;

-network and make contacts

&nbsp;

-freely promote your work via the " # postpromotion link (no more than once every two hours)

&nbsp;

-join different, niche focused channels to promote and discuss different content

&nbsp;

-get in touch with more experienced "Steemians" most of whom will be happy to offer some assistance. You might even meet a whale or two.

&nbsp;
<h2>WHAT MAKES STEEMIT UNIQUE?</h2>
<span style="font-size: 19px;"></span>

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89" custom_padding="5px|0px|0px|0px"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_image src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1465223583124-fc76419637e1?ixlib=rb-0.3.5&amp;ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&amp;s=68109388b4f7e5ac234037a8885c1190&amp;auto=format&amp;fit=crop&amp;w=500&amp;q=60" _builder_version="3.0.89" align="center"][/et_pb_image][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89" custom_padding="30px|0px|0px|0px"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_text _builder_version="3.0.89"]

First, all content is encoded into the Steemit blockchain in the form of text. This renders it into an immutable form. It is also permanently linked with the account that posted it forming a kind of crypto-wallet-content-portfolio of sorts. It is an amazing example of one of the many, many potential uses for this kind of technology and the way the platform incentivises and stimulates content creation, curation and discussion. As Steemit also has its own cryptocurrency available on many of the majore exchanges, the typical as well as all the other typical activity of a solid cryptocurrency platform is nothing short of amazing.

Next there is the way the platform is incentivized. Posters are rewarded based on the number of upvotes they receive in <a href="https://coinmarketcap.com/currencies/steem/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">STEEM</a>tokens, Steemit's own cryptocurrency. These tokens are tradeable on cryptoexchanges just as any other cryptocurrency is.There is thus a kind of two way flow in the sense that value can be built both 1) based on the quality of content itself and also 2) via open market speculation and trading. And, so far, Steemit is proving to be a very fungible platform indeed.

The STEEM tokens are delegated as they are minted according to, among other things, the general trends in upvoting (more on this later). So there is no imbalance of power or bias to certain 3rd party entities and patrons controlling/censoring what content does and doesn't receive attention; although there is an option for users to flag content should they feel it is too illicit.

With other, more traditional platfoms like Facebook and Google etc. it is not always the quality of the content that fuels its popularity but the amount of capital (3rd party or otherwise) injected into promoting it. This is not, of course,<em>always</em> the case but it can be enough of an obstacle that it is worth mentioning. SEO is still a powerful force in the online world as is generating a large social media following via organic promotion of quality content. However, it still remains the case that a party with enough money can more or less bypass this process by simply flatteining the competition with their advertising budget.

Conversely, on Steemit, no such option exists. Upvotes and the resultant social following can only be earned via organic growth. People have to like your content and you have to make the effort of networking and building an audience yourself. Your audience must be earned and not bought.

The main idea behind the Steemit platform is that <em>the quality of content not the wallet of the party creating it drives its reception and monetization.</em>A rough analogy could be the way a website attains a higher and higher ranking in search engine results based on the quality of its content and the number of organic links and traffic connecting to it. Only, on Steemit, instead of ranking we are talking about a higher delegation of Steemit tokens. The more tokens you receive, the more money you make.

&nbsp;
<h2>HOW THE MONEY PART WORKS</h2>
[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89" custom_padding="0px|0px|0px|0px"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_image src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1517448988499-4cdc5bbde64c?ixlib=rb-0.3.5&amp;ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&amp;s=10450b1daa31a8955a2ef99a35c87d85&amp;auto=format&amp;fit=crop&amp;w=500&amp;q=60" _builder_version="3.0.89"][/et_pb_image][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89" custom_padding="30px|0px|0px|0px"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_text _builder_version="3.0.89"]
<h2></h2>
Posters on Steemit are compensated for their creative work<em>directly</em> by their readers, via the Steemit blockchain, and not according to the whims of a 3rd party owner of the platform. This is a concrete application of blockchain at work in what Vitalik Buterin, founder of Ethereum, is talking about when he talks about "the democratization of power".

However, readers are not required to donate any actual funds themselves. Instead, the act of upvoting a piece will delegate more prioirity to that piece and so allow it to accrue more Steem tokens as they are minted via the generation of new blocks on the Steemit blockchain. That is, the blockchain generates new cryptocurrency which is delegated to content creators and curators on Steemit <em>automatically.</em> Basically, the flow of new Steemit tokens being minted is told where to go according to the number of upvotes and their aggregation around content. <em>There is no 3rd party controlling this.</em> The only agents involved are the content creators, the audience and the blockchain (along with those managing it). It is actually somewhat difficult to overstate what an ingenious system this is. It is essentially a 100% democratic and objective method of rewarding content creation based solely on its reception by the audience viewing it.

As the founders of Steemit say themselves in regard to how the platform differs from other social media websites:
<h2><em>"While most social media sites extract this value for the benefit of their shareholders, Steemit believes that the users of the platform should receive the benefits and rewards for their attention and the contributions they make to the platform."</em></h2>
&nbsp;
<h2>GIVING IT BACK TO THE PEOPLE</h2>
This is an amazing service to serious content creators and an ingenious use of blockchain technology; something old <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satoshi_Nakamoto" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Mr. Nakamoto</a>, wherever he may be, could be proud of. The Steemit blockchain is essentially doing for online content creators what the Bitcoin Blockchain has done for online finance and that is to remove all but the most essential elements of a digital transaction and to place the integrity, identity and control of it in the hands of the end users alone. The end users on Steemit of course being the content creator and their audience.

For too long artists and creators of every kind have been more or less at the mercy of 3rd party intermediaries in control of what work is acceptable, how it is accepted and how any financial proceeds are delegated. Talent, unfortunately, has fared rather poorly against marketing forces that simply don't care for the nature of the content being presented. The internet has, to a large, degree succeeded in combating the effective monopoly large firms and wealthy individuals have historically enjoyed over artisans and creators. Such platforms as Wordpress and Youtube, to name a few, are final examples of technologies that empower individual content creators in ways inconceivable only a decade or two ago. Yet they are still very much victim of the insidious problems concerning 3rd party regulation. Namely, lack of full control over one's content/transaction, security and representation to name only a few.

Steemit, while technically a 3rd party in the sense of serving as a platform where end users gather to create, curate and consume content takes things a step further by involving account holders<em>directly</em> in the financial action occurring on the platform. There is currently no other platform in the world doing quite what Steemit is doing which is to combine the stability of blockchain technology and the independence of decentralized cryptocurrencies with human creativity. The implications of this, if you have any understanding of any of the elements involved at all, are really pretty amazing. There are many who speak of blockchain technology as "Internet 2.0" or "the next stage in the evolution of the internet" and so on. Steemit, it would seem, is a perfect example made manifest by this line of thinking.

&nbsp;
<h2>A LIL' DOSE OF REALITY</h2>
<h2></h2>
[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_image src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518173184999-0381b5eb56d7?ixlib=rb-0.3.5&amp;ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&amp;s=1eba0fe82659f0e447559d9f80c8dc9e&amp;auto=format&amp;fit=crop&amp;w=500&amp;q=60" _builder_version="3.0.89" align="center"][/et_pb_image][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_text _builder_version="3.0.89"]
<h2></h2>
Of course, while the Steemit platform is in itself an amazing system to share content and potentially make a living doing it, it is not all so easy. The universal challenges of creating the content and building an audience for it are still there. Creators still need the technical fluency to create good content in the first place and the know-how to promote it in the second. So, as with any creative endeavor it is partly a labor of love and partly a long term investment of one's own time and energy in sharing what one hopes other people will like. And there are no guarantees. However, the structure of the platform is truly unique and there are, even so early into the game, creators making significant sums for the posts on Steemit. The general user would be advised, however, to put this into perspective and take a look at the sheer amount of content these "Steemit whales", as they are called, have produced and the number of followers they have. It is often a very revealing thing to do.

This is not to disuade the would be Steemian from the platform. Not at all. It is simply to say that, as with any real artist no matter how talented, there is an unavoidable element of commitment and determination that must be put in to the work; "true grit", as it were. Personally, I have lamented at not getting involved in now very well established platforms earlier. As a writer and businessman, I am more than willing to devote the hard, long and solitary hours to the work but the question has always been one of targeting and reach. Being that it is still very early days with the Steemit platform, there is likely more potential and opportunity than ever. As long as you are willing to put the work in.

&nbsp;
<h2>HOW IT WORKS: A LOOK AT THE BLUEPAPER</h2>
[/et_pb_text][et_pb_image src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1471107340929-a87cd0f5b5f3?ixlib=rb-0.3.5&amp;ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&amp;s=395debe4f66b27cd8fb346d73cffb70c&amp;auto=format&amp;fit=crop&amp;w=500&amp;q=60" _builder_version="3.0.89" align="center"][/et_pb_image][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89" custom_padding="0px|0px|30px|0px"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_text _builder_version="3.0.89"]

The best advice we can give if you really want to learn how the platform works would be to read the <a href="https://steem.io/steem-bluepaper.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Steem Bluepaper</a>. It is extremely well written and concise in explaining the structure and dynamics of the platform. So some of its more pertinent points will be quoted here simply because it would be difficult to state them any better than the original work does itself. The following will be, however, more of a general and simplified explanation.

The essential feature of the Steemit platform is what is called in the Bluepaper "Proof Of Brain" (an admitted entendre of Bitcoin's "Proof Of Work" mining system) which is designed to highlight the human effort in back of how exactly value is assigned and agreed upon by the Steemit community. To quote the bluepaper:

&nbsp;
<h2><em>Token systems that reward users as they contribute to a token-based community system require</em><em>mechanisms for establishing and evaluating contents social value: we call this Proof-of-Brain.</em></h2>
&nbsp;

What this essentially means is a fusion of both the "smart" blockchain technology and its tokenized rewards system with the "social" aspect of human creativity or, as the Bluepaper puts it "a voting system that leverages the wisdom of the crowd to assess the value of content and distribute tokens to it".

This leveraging of "the wisdom of the crowd" should be simple enough to understand and is essentially the same as "likes" on Facebook. What is unique about Steemit is its fusion of this social system with a true blue blockchain based cryptocurrency the delegation of which is determined by the number of upvotes for a given piece of content. That is, after the tokens are minted, the amount alotted for content creators will be automatically delegated to them in amounts relative to the number of upvotes given to their work.

&nbsp;

Both the Steem blockchain and token are highly optimized for high transaction numbers per second and, by their socially incentivized nature, high volume traffic across the internet. Steem uses aDPoS (Delegated Proof of Stake ) blockchain on which blocks are created at a fixed interval of 1 every 3 seconds using a fraction of the computational load of the more well-known Proof Of Work algorithm that is making Bitcoin increasingly more expensive and resource intensive to mine. What this means is that "the [Steemit] blockchain can process more transactions and hold more information, including content." Both very nice capacities indeed for a platform that will likely see adoption and use increase by multiple levels of magnitude in the coming years.

&nbsp;

Anyone with any familiarity with the current state of the world of blockchain and cryptocurrencies will know that the two most popular platforms, Bitcoin and Ethereum, currently struggle with their low rate of transactions per second. Basically, neither of them would ever be able to handle any full scale, global type of implementation.

&nbsp;

On the contrary, the Steem blockchain is currently the busiest in the world. And, according to <a href="https://cryptocoinspy.com/steem-announces-1-millionth-account-and-more-daily-traffic-than-all-other-blockchains-combined/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">this article</a>, is currently seeing more traffic and successful transactions than all other blockchain platforms in the world <em>combined. </em>And, thanks to the type of blockchain it runs on, it isshowing no signs of any major structural shortcomings.

&nbsp;
<h2>THE REWARDS POOL</h2>
&nbsp;

The rewards pool is the term given to STEEM tokens available for distribution after minting. The percentage of their allotment to different parties is fixed at the following rates:

&nbsp;
<ul>
 	<li>75% to content creators and curators</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;
<ul>
 	<li>15% to vested token holders</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;
<ul>
 	<li>10% to witnesses (roughly equivalent to the "miners" on the Bitcoin and Ethereum blockchain).</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;

Analysis of this distribution structure should give sufficient understanding as to how the "Steemit economy" is able to function and, moreover, the immense and currently latent potential for growth it has. It is conceivable that, in the years to come, good content creators who have put in the time and effort to build a loyal audience could potentially make a full time living from their work to say nothing of how the witnesses and vested token holders could also benefit.

&nbsp;

Both <a href="https://www.coingecko.com/en/coins/steem/trading_exchanges" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Steem</a> and <a href="https://coincodex.com/crypto/steem-dollars/exchanges/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">STEEM Dollars</a> (a different crypto in function) can be bought on various crypto currency exchanges. However, all STEEM tokens are born on the Steemit blockchain before heading out on their own, as it were, for trade on the crypto exchanges. Both currencies, incidentally, have weathered the violent fluctuations and downturns of the market in early 2018 remarkably well. Logic would say this is largely because they are one of the currently very few cryptocurrencies that are seeing valid market use.

&nbsp;
<h2>IMPRESSIONS OF THE PLATFORM</h2>
[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89" custom_padding="0px|0px|0px|0px"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_image src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1445912842705-7ee858b234c9?ixlib=rb-0.3.5&amp;ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&amp;s=04bde96592ef985e6983b30695e33624&amp;auto=format&amp;fit=crop&amp;w=500&amp;q=60" _builder_version="3.0.89" align="center"][/et_pb_image][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_text _builder_version="3.0.89"]

At first I was somewhat struck by the simple appearance of the site and its lack of flare. A quick visit to steemit.com will present you with a very simple menu and the top articles currently trending. Personally, I like this approach as it focuses the visitor on the content and speaks to the democratic, direct and, for lack of a better term, "non-cheesy" approach to content presentation that seems to characterize the platform as a whole.

&nbsp;

As you get more familiar with the platform and visit different articles you will likely come to appreciate the ease of use and the direct way of interfacing with both authors and those discussing their work.

&nbsp;

It is extremely easy to get in touch with people and to follow their work if you like what you see. There currently seem to be a number of different communities developing on Steemit and I was quite surprised by the general tone of the community and everyone's willingness to help when I had a question. It is indeed a very friendly place for bloggers and content creators of all sorts. All users are delegated a "reputation score" and the data concerning their account's wallet, followers and those the account holder is following are clearly viewable for all (even if you don't have an account).

&nbsp;

Despite the somewhat Spartan impression the layout of the site may give it does seem that there has been an extreme degree of thought put into the general structure and nagivability of it along with a user's capacity to interact with other account holders.

&nbsp;
<h2>PROBLEMS?</h2>
&nbsp;

Given that the platform is still relatively new and seeing incredible growth at the same time. There have been occurences of bugs and anomolies. The builders of the site freely admit this themselves and are doing their best to streamline the user experience while helping the platform to scale as its popularity continues to grow. A quick look at the site will also reveal that the platform is still in Beta mode.

&nbsp;

From time to time there are sometimes glitches and errors concerning the posting of content but this seems mostly due to the increasing volume of traffic and transactions on the platform. It is, after all, a new and, more importantly, revolutionary thing. Such things rarely have the smoothest of debuts but do tend to have a lasting effect once they reach stability.

&nbsp;

There is also considerable chatter on the internet concerning long wait times to get Steemit accounts approved. Again, this is likely simply because of the high volume of new applicants swamping the team in charge of approving new accounts.

&nbsp;

The builders of the platform themselves freely adimit to these issues and go so far as to say that it will become easier to use as time goes on. Launching such a platform is no small undertaking and they have seen incredible growth from 0 to 1,000,000 accounts in less than two years.

&nbsp;

The only real problem, however, is the same that most social and content oriented internet platforms: scammers.

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_image src="https://cdn.steemitimages.com/0x0/http://s2.quickmeme.com/img/88/88604c59aeae09d8f7be7d42c6267972aa3b4e64e454778ad0f9192d627b4d95.jpg" _builder_version="3.0.89" align="center"][/et_pb_image][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.0.89"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.0.89" parallax="off" parallax_method="on"][et_pb_text _builder_version="3.0.89"]

Yes, there are certain account holders of a less than ethical nature seeking to undermine, hack, steal and generally create mayhem for you. Steemit is no exception. So be careful about

&nbsp;
<ul>
 	<li>who you follow</li>
 	<li>who you respond to</li>
 	<li>any 3rd party links you click on</li>
 	<li>and never ever, ever, ever share your password (or any account information) with anyone who doesn't absolutely have a need to know (which is likely <em>everyone except you</em>).</li>
</ul>
Aside from the typical destructive dumbasses that seem to inhabit just about every corner of the internet, the majority of issues with the platform to date are mostly cosmetic. And just about all of them can be boiled down to the typical issues faced by any platform when encountering the relentless and pressing demands of scalability. I am sure that, with future development and growth, Steemit will be a force to be reckoned with (in a good way) in both the worlds of social media and content creation in general.

The fact that it is also built in with its own blockchain and native cryptocurrency is very exciting as well.
<h2>FUTURE</h2>
Personally, I remain very optomistic about the future of both the Steemit platform and the content creators who will put the time and work into building their audiences. It is such a unique combination of elements: blockchain, cryptocurrency and human creativity. It will be a very interesting ride and, for those who stick with it, likely a prosperous one, too.

If you are interested in signing up for Steemit, <a href="https://steemit.com/">click here</a>. It is absolutely free. You can also feel free to follow me there. My name is @technoguy. Another nice thing about the platform is that you are free to post a variety of content in different niches. It is a surprisingly active community and you likely won't regret getting involved.

